And in this particular climate, yesterday, 85 deputies of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most of the Liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the Constitution was announced, they slammed through the door, saying they did not have the opportunity to assert their views.
Defenders of human rights, civil society or members of religious minorities have imitated their move.
In order to achieve a quorum, 11 alternate replacements were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising then that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators went on to pause to say that one of the few disputes revolved around . . . a prayer class that day, when some committee members took the view that the hours in the meeting room were not properly adjusted.
The text, which was still voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, remains the same as that of the 1971 Constitution, and states that "sharia law principles are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the essential requirements, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules," which would allow for a stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected represents a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Hyrability," the liberals, who see only a rhetorical problem, object.
In their view, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts the University of al-Azhar with an advisory role, in particular to the issues of the monitoring of the conformity of Sharia law.
According to Egypt's expert, Sophie Pommier, this is unsettling because "persons called for comment are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
