Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulamas, but university staff, many of whom have graduated from French schools," says Alexis Blouet, who is preparing work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that "there may be contradictions about the interpretation of Article 220, because the terms used in it belong to the religious vocabulary.
There is a reference in particular to "fiqh" [Islamic Legal Science].
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to comment on it."
The text approved yesterday is highly criticised in addition to the religious sites because of the expanded powers that it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant reduction in them compared to the former regime.
Another contentious place: powers conferred on the military.
In accordance with the wishes of the military's representatives, the defence budget will not be carried out by parliament, but by the National Defence Council.
