In an interview with Aktuálně.cz, the vice-president of the Supreme Audit Office, Miloslav Kala, says so.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be right - that's what I think is missing from us," Kala comments on the current situation.
Similar conclusions are also indicated by the joint control of Czech and German controllers.
As an example of an incorrect practice, he cites Petr Nečas's approach to the so-called "švarcsystem".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with his controls - is it forbidden or permitted?
"The law must be somehow set up, and if it prohibits something, even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the activities of the office, which is obliged to go to check and enforce obligations," Kala says.
At a meeting of the Audit Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke of a joint project between the Czech and German parties, in which the legislation on public procurement in both countries was compared.
What exactly was going on?
This is a parallel check, which we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, the point is that European legislation regulates how to address public procurement, followed by individual national legislation and then also by the practice itself.
We have put all this together, and although the control is not yet completed, we have shown very interesting differences - in general, the legislation is perhaps "more stricter and better" in our country, but the practice itself is better in some parameters.
It is confirmed, then, that it is not enough to create more and further precise rules, but it is necessary to address the actual application of the law.
What can this project actually help you do, what does it come from it?
It is such joint control that could contribute to the stop of efforts to refine the laws, reduce and improve the limits when it does not have such a positive impact.
Economicality means getting the right thing to be reasonable (which does not always mean the lowest) price to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal conduct.
But by lowering the contract limit, we do not necessarily achieve this.
Maybe the system will be overwhelmed with so much of the "paper" that those who want to look for holes in that system will draw on it a lot more easily than if the limit would stay higher.
You are talking about domestic problems with transposing public procurement legislation.
How does the control system in Germany work?
Is the office similar to our SAO, or is it set up differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, as the SAO operates there the Bundesrechnungshof, which is organised in the same way as we are, also has a college, only forming in a slightly different way, but in principle the two authorities are acting similarly.
The powers are also similar to a certain extent, but in the fact that Germany has a federal arrangement, so it has these accounting courts at the level of the various Länder - in this, the system differs a bit from ours.
The BRH can only control the federal money, represented by the state funds in our country.
Public funds that are managed by the counties and municipalities in our country are checked from the level of the federal accounting courts.
As far as the legislation there is, is that easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare it without specific data, however, in some respects Germany is often referred to as a model, but it is certainly not to be said to be better at everything.
So is this also the fact that they have better controllers?
I'm sure I'm not, but I'm saying again, I don't like that kind of comparisons.
But it has to be said that even countries that we consider a role model face a whole range of problems.
Otherwise, it would be of no use to cooperate with our office, would it?
As for the domestic legislation, what did the amendment to the Public Procurement Act mean for your office, are there any effect on its effects?
Since the validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been reflected in the inspection events in our country.
Because we are doing ex-post checks, we need to expect some delays.
We only observe this so far in the process of preparing future inspections - we have kick-started our new "detachation of risk of inefficiency" through which we have laced almost 14,000 public contracts, and we have analysed them - there, of course, the changes will be reflected there, because the limits will change, the conditions of some types of tenders will be adjusted and the like.
Do you therefore consider the approval of this law to be more of an asset or a further burden on the red tape system?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction, and I hope that's confirmed.
A problem that may arise here that the rules will be "stretched" and it will not be possible to comply with them.
Already under the functioning of the previous rules, the audited persons are bound by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes by the Regional Council) to the fact that any non-compliance with the Public Procurement Act entails a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it therefore worth tightening the law in this way?
I think not in this way.
The system must exclude those who want to challenge and abuse it, and not punish those who commit a formal misconduct that has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more pressure on the bureaucracy.
How do you get out of it, then?
Let's show where the road is not.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not harass entrepreneurs by inspecting the so-called 'chartagic' - and what does that mean?
Is the ŠvarcSystota forbidden or allowed?
After all, the law must be set up somehow, and if it does, if it does forbid something, then even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the work of the office, which is obliged to go to check and enforce obligations.
He can say, "We'll change the law and we'll pass it on," but he can't say we're going to act like nothing.
There are fairly strict rules in the Public Procurement Act on how what is to be done formally - which is rightly to protect the public tender.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the bidder with the best bid is excluded only for formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - that is what I think is missing from us.
