Šimon Ornest: We want to gather positive energy at concerts
What do you think of the end of the world coming to an end for less than a month?
It's just one of the other alarms that we humans like to catch on.
Together with the band The Tap Tap, we make more of a joke about it and say that we are the only band in the world who can gather enough positive energy to delay or prevent the end of the world.
In addition, in December you will organize a completely unique project three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce it to your readers?
This is a national fundraiser that we have been planning for two years.
We decided to tap into the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar announced on December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before 20 December from 21:00 will be held in parallel for 3 concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end around the time the Mayan calendar will end on the island of Kiribati in the Pacific, which is 12 hours ahead of us in the time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
Originally it was probably my idea, after which we invented everything together with our artist Honza Augusta.
In addition to the fact that we want to amass enough positive energy and prevent the end of the world, we also want to think, together with the public, about the state in which we will one day pass this world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we also created a unique collection of items of shoes, T-shirts, bags or original keys against the end of the world, which people can also support us by purchasing at www.e-tap.cz.
The Tap Tap, along with other performers, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, which is called "The End of the World Cancelled."
Already today she is very popular on YouTube, will she also be heard at these benefit concerts?
Of course, at the very end, that is, if we can all do and the end of the world...
It is sung by all performers at all three concerts in parallel.
The anthems will suddenly also be linked in a unique live broadcast on Czech Television.
The words for this song were written and the lead role of Jesus in the clip is played by Tomáš Hanák, it is also sung by Xindl X...
How did you get to work with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, given that we organize a lot of benefit events and concerts...
We are trying to engage them intensively in these projects.
It turns out that most of them are interested and entertaining to work with us.
What will the proceeds from the concerts against the end of the world go for?
To equip the barrier-free education centre Studeo, which we have been implementing for the sixth year with the civic association Tap in the Jedlička Institute.
For school students of the Jedlička Institute, lecturers regularly attend to them in activities they enjoy and interest.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to the lecturers themselves, so we try to allow them to do so in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building will be created in the future to which we will move with this project.
Each concert will feature several musical groups and performers.
How did you choose them?
We were trying to put together a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere will perform perform with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bangoo and Jiří Suchý.
Read all the details at www.kpks.cz.
Are you planning any similar "omball events" for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, so we will certainly prepare an interesting programme with interesting guests here as well.
Next year we would also like to play at the Czech National House in New York, and I personally, while we are in the US, I would like to link it to performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not minimalist, you have performed so far in, for example, Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is nevertheless a group made up of handicapped people.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it first appears.
We have five members on an electric cart, their carts have to travel in the luggage compartment, then of course we are lugging with us a large number of cargo and boxes of tools...
However, so far it has always been done without any problems, with CSA and British Airways both beautifully prepared for us that I have wondered how many times.
Even in Moscow, from which we came back recently, it was no problem.
With trips abroad, you can compare how the different ones differ in barrier-free, public access to the handicapped and the like.
What have you encountered so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than ours, we have just seen in Russia that everything is still in the very beginning in the east.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is very barrier-free, here it is still unusual for a person on an electric cart to move in the city centre.
It is not even of such obvious that you prefer wheelchair users in the lift.
Fortunately, civic associations are already being formed there, too, to try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way, on the other hand, do we still have to catch up with more mature countries?
There's a lot of things we're still behind...
But it is important to mention that improving and improving the situation is always dependent on the efforts of the people involved.
In both London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with a heavy handicap to move independently in public, to go to the toilet, to the museum, to wherever...
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to actively participate in social life, in this we are a little bit ahead with The Tap Tap!
Respecting the public or barrier-free is one thing, but only when we become important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers will start to change in the first place.
So far, these are isolated cases of people with a strong will.
The band The Tap Tap is now very popular, but let's go back a few years since you made you start it in 1998?
I joined as a tutor at the Jedlička Institute, where I had many young people around who were interested in doing something.
And since I am a musician myself, I play, among other things, the saxophone, I started a special-interest music club with a colleague.
Well, over time, as our presenter Lada Angelovich says, it got a little out of hand (laughter).
But the popularity came only in the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that it helped us when we started to connect with the well-known singers and also to actively work to promote the band.
We realized that a job that you can't see really doesn't seem to exist.
In addition, thanks to the contributions from the European Union, we can afford quality lecturers, equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to make it this high with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do something differently.
Showbusiness is crowded with things where one mimics another.
It's kind of logical, everything new is accepted cautiously, and it takes a long time.
Things that are unique are very few, but I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression in the person who sees us for the first time is, of course, regret, that's natural...
But the regret is completely in vain, because the handicap people are not suffering from all the abandoned beings we must regret.
These are people who can live a full life and develop, provided, of course, the means to do so.
I say that when people with a handicap get something right, it's not just a shift for them, it's for the whole of society.
Did this success also be the fact that you are a strict boss, as many people have called you?
When we want to do quality work, we have to be uncompromising about many things and demand a certain discipline.
But I think that's perfectly normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic image and a head in the clouds, and when they find out that they have to go to the exam twice the week, attend the product and spend a lot of time on the road to the concerts, the enthusiasm quickly leaves them.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and who wants to achieve something.
The band Tap Tap currently has 20 members.
How many of them were at her beginnings in 1998?
Only one Lada Angelovic.
We're an open group, people are leaving and coming, you can't be prevented from doing that.
Whoever has the will and the taste always has the door open with us
