Last week, at a ministerial ministerial meeting of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of this European Space Agency, as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in a number of of Agency projects over the following years.
However, Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
The flight to space was attended to by Polish enthusiasts before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I will mention, for example, the A. Šternfelda in the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on 6 December 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work The Entrance to Space.
The ideas of a young engineer (b. 1905) left the listener cold and after years Šternfeld recalled that only dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hircha Award for the Go to Space in France.
The recalled Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and spaceflight.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-famous promoter of spaceflight, and his contribution was also praised by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named by his name.
Already in 1925 a railroad was built in Poland, which was to be fitted with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket was to be used to run the torsion or to brake it.
The information about this trench is only known from the period press.
