However, the arrival of the German troops was interrupted by the research.
In 1937, a design of a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the professional press, and in the following year the work of Rakieta - the torpedo powietrzna and the rakietobomba of the lotbook by the author Leliwy-Krzywoblocký was published.
Both projects were intended for the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all military-use projects of missile technology were addressed by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities ceased the start of the war.
Other work devoted to spaceflight appears in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronaut Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautycz).
It is first mentioned in the November issue of the 1954 magazine Problems, in which there are four more comprehensive articles dedicated to astronautics.
In one of them, by Prof. M. Subotowicz, is proposed to create a company to deal with spaceflight.
By then, artificial satellite projects were already underway, and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronaut Society (PTA) of the Polish Astronautical Society (founded 1951) and became a full member in the autumn.
And in the following year, the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became vice-chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this post until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful Meteorological rocket RM (Racieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10. October 1958.
The missile with a range of 1,800 metres was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
An improved version of the RM-1A was later built, and in the summer of 1959, the flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 missile were launched in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 metres long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
Another development type should have been capable of real scientific work by now - the RM-34 rocket was to have a range of up to 14.5 km and was tasked with tracking the altitude wind.
However, in 1962 further development was suspended.
The first RM rockets were the A Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, total length of 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (marked by Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, differing in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket, a 0.4-litre space, a Meteor-1B 0.34-litre Meteor-1C and a 0.62-litre Meteor-1C was available.
The maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the AMet-2, a Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Auschwaiti Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, versions of the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR national committee two years later.
