This is the case for Anta Wijay, one of the 400 miners who make his living by conquering sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, they have to fry every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphur gases are leaked from the inside of the Earth and, when in contact with the air, they pass into a solid state.
After choping up large sulfur blocks, which together weigh up to 70 kilos, he carries them on the shoulders in two bamboo baskets along the steep stone trails.
To the top of the volcano, which towered 2,386 metres, it is only 250 metres, but it takes the exhausted carriers over 40 minutes to climb up the turtledist pace as they keep their balance and carefully consider their steps to avoid slipping and crash into the abyss.
They know that any stumble could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who collapsed from the rocks of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
When they're up there, they make their way past the tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in the circus, and wearily carry heavy baskets to the vase that the mining company has placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1850 metres.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has benefited in the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers to more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulphur.
It is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even whitening of sugar.
"Because it is normally 70 kilos worn, we earn about 46,000 rupees (€3.8) for each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
One trip takes him three hours and is destroyed at the end, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (€11.5) per day.
While this seems to be a negligible amount for such an inhumane effort, it is three times what he would make in the field.
"The miners' wages are very high here. For example, collecting coffee is paid for 15,000 rupees (€1.2) per day, and the salary for a fortnight is two million rupees (€166))," explains the porter who previously worked on the tourist island of Bali as a bricklayer.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees (€6.2) per day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason, which is as convincing in Indonesia as sulphur: "I married a young girl from Bali, who is Hindu, and I took her to Jávu to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, he's hard to breathe, he's still coughing and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto risks living in the Kawah Ijen volcano three times a day, the sulfur of which has already begun to take its toll on it, even though his face is protected by a special mask and goggles.
He has asthma, he can't breathe, he's coughing all the time, and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that escape from the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to get his dream.
"I will work for two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises more than a decent English.
This likeable and intelligent young man, troubled by his fate, could be a tourist guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, and instead does the work of a porter.
She shares a dirty wooden shack with other porters and gets up at two o'clock every day because the sulphur continues to rise at night and its characteristic yellow color turns blue and glowing with darkness.
Despite the surrounding darkness, the pharates of Anto to the crater, illuminating his way with a small lantern, which he has attached to his helmet and bought it himself with his money.
About 400 porters carry a sulfur basket from the crater's bottom of the crater
Although the company has high incomes, it has not stabilized the extraction of sulfur because of cost savings, nor does it provide the carriers working on their own and with such effort, no equipment.
In fact, they do not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (€2.5) from the photography supplement, which, together with a 15,000-sized ticket (€1.2.), is collected by the nature park keepers from tourists arriving to take pictures of the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for the cattle, and not for the people," says Madrusin, a burly 42-year-old carrier who has worked at Kawah Ijen for three decades, ever since he left the schools.
He can do a lift up to 110 kilos and assures us that he can work "as long as he can" work because he needs the money to educate his three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life
Although sulfur burns its throat and stings in its eyes, when the wind unexpectedly turns and traps the miners in the dense fumes that emanate from the volcano, the miners are so claiming that none of them complain of suffering from serious illnesses... but this is evident from their frequent respiratory problems, arthritis, knee pain and wounds on the shoulders caused by the weight of the baskets.
The Unainik who balances his basket on his back can only load 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his colleagues dig out 15 tons of sulfur in the volcano, which the three trucks then take the steep road between the thicket to the warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometres away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life," Unainik declares, opening a wide mouth in which several teeth are missing.
Of his five sons, the eldest, the 30-year-old, also earns the earlift by mining.
Time passes, but the incessant misery of one of the world's most difficult crafts persists from generation to generation - the crafts performed by human mules in Kawah Iljen.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans are seduced by not having children, careers, stress, and the cost of living and education.
"The people of Singapore need to grow."
I'm married and I'm a patriot, and you're my wife and you're a patriot. Let's fulfill our civic duty and spawn a new life!
It may seem incredible that this slogan is part of a hoop-bonus ad, but still - or perhaps because of it - the video in Singapore this year was expanded en masse to YouTube in Singapore.
These theorems are part of the rap used by local innuendos, which uses the "we put the buckle in the oven" as a mockery of the fertility rate in Singapore.
The advertising agency BBH, which created the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a funny way with this ad.
The agency's art director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the influence of music to make people live up to "his civic duty."
"This is strictly an Internet issue, so it must have been fun and funny.
It is the biggest problem in this country.
We're the worst in the world in reproducing our population, so we felt like it was a topic we had to touch.
We knew the government was trying to do a lot of things like expanding pheromone perfumes or organizing dating parties.
Many of these ideas might have been creative, but not entirely functional.
So we thought, why not do the most creative possible thing, such as the composition of the rap, to solve the problem."
1.2 children
Whoever doesn't take it too lightly is the Singaporean government.
They spend $1,300 a year to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government's marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and allocates financial benefits.
But all of these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, advanced-tech urban state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and strict social controls.
The fertility rate in Singapore, with a view to stratifying the population, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the birth rate exceeded the birth rate, which is considered to be the rate of renewal, in 1976.
Why do Singaporeans have no more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Marriage and Family Department of the National Population Agency says it's because of "imaginable education" and "a wider range of career opportunities."
"People have a wider range of options at their disposal when it comes to life's goals and priorities, it's not just a wedding and a family," he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to increasing the number of single people and to postponing marriages and proclamations of children. The result is a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
While immigration policy included efforts to drastically increase the flow of immigrants as a measure against a decline in the population, this has provoked resentment among the locals.
Some Singaporean websites show undisguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticised for maintaining low pay and making little effort to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the governing Singapore party recorded its worst election result since the start of independence last year.
After the election, there was an effort to address the problem by using quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has seen effects on national economic growth, tax revenues, health-care spending, and immigration policies, and there have also been some unexpected consequences for Singapore.
The government is trying to keep buildings of so many small houses.
For example, it began to influence the real estate business.
The Municipal Development Office has begun to regulate the number of small apartments known as "footboxes" that can be built in certain urban areas.
These flats have an area of 46 square metres and have been a great success in sales.
However, there is a fear that these apartments can support the bachelor's lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the developer's EL Developers, says their "shoisboxes" sell far faster than larger homes.
"They're more popular, by selling for days to weeks faster than larger-scale houses.
That's why they're much better for our cash flow."
However, it admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously capped when they wanted to offer too many small houses in a single project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
Although these new rules could aim to increase the nation's fertility rate, a conversation with the Singaporeans working in the financial district of the city centre suggests that they will not have much effect.
"People are still stressed, houses are expensive, as are education, so do many people postpone it," says the young official.
"The others have children.
But for me it is important to rely on my own money and time," says another, about 20-year-old, a young man.
Both men and women mention their careers, stress, and the cost of living and education as reasons preventing them from having children.
So however the government tries to force citizens to have children, it is the Singaporeans who have the last word on starting a family.
What is private offline is both private and online
Privacy.
According to a dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something of a personal nature or "the publicity of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any disturbance."
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes on the Internet matters he would certainly not have told anyone in his normal communications?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent internet users.
In four cases, the notion of privacy considered "something entirely of its own" on a personal level and a "user name and password" if it was social networks.
"My biggest secret I wouldn't have published," says 10-year-old Jorge, in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom can know about them, but not the whole world," he claims.
"I put nice pictures or pictures on FB playing.
I'm also talking to my friends there.
I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine, or a picture that would make someone ridiculed," he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine Twitter followers.
Most of them are related.
Among them is the mother, who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I started a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone can answer me, I just put them there," he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicate with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended someone to the unknown.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks, and admits to the latest network that he does not know 20 people on his list of friends.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them pointed him out, nor did he want him to address or phone number.
"If they urged me or required it from me, I would simply remove them from my account," he admits.
Jose signed up for Ask after reading the Twitter recommendation.
This boy is no stranger to experience with what is now called cyberbullying (cyberbullying).
"The well-known friend was blackmailed on the social networking site.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never learned who it was," he confirms.
The victim, according to Jose, did not resign from her account.
"She just activated her private mode."
Then he explains a series of steps to safely set the account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post pictures of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would do it if someone bothered me or just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and a graduate in Education and Teaching, believes that in order to navigate children and adolescents correctly in social networks, they must understand that the main objective of these networks is to inform.
He states that: "The internet originated as a means of seeking information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and author of the article Digital Reagents and digital immigrants, introduced these terms to explain the phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born during the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, yet we are still learning ourselves," he says.
He explains that it is a complex subject "because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to disseminate, publish and say, and what not to say, at an age when they are not yet mature for it."
Also, to be - as far as the surroundings are concerned - to be deliberate, at a time when what they most desire is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is to ask questions that make them think.
"To tell them not to do something doesn't work," he adds.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the possibilities: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like to see someone posting your picture the way you posted a friend's?
You know what other people are publishing about you?
When you tag the people in the pictures of the celebrations, did you ask these people's permission?
And one more: Do they all need to know what you're doing right now?
The next point is to make them realise that they have to behave in the internet environment the same as they do outside of it.
It's the same rules.
"You are guided by respect, morality and other principles outside the internet, and one should be the same on social networks," he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, a first-grade teacher and an educational adviser, explains the need for children's parents to carefully read the rules of social networks.
"If they understand every tricky nature, they have a good basis to talk to their children about the consequences that setting up an online account can have.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or published," he says.
The Guardia is of the opinion that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional "not to talk to strangers" rule.
The South American Summit Ends and the Lima Declaration Has Not Disclosed
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru ended today without the Speaking of the Lima Declaration, which was announced and was reportedly signed by the seven presidents present.
The eahead agency has repeatedly attempted to gain access to a document signed at the sixth meeting of Unasur's Heads of State or Government, but representatives of both the Foreign Ministry and the presidential office, who initially stipulated that they would publish the document after the summit ended, said it would be published later on the Peruvian government's website.
They also said that the content was released by Peru's President Ollanta Humala in several short press releases.
Journalists had their access to information restricted throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video of the presidential assembly was transmitted in the press room without sound with the message " confidential session, sound transmission prevented."
A small amount of information available to journalists was provided by the press spokespersons of some of the governments who were present, but not the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document published during the meeting was the list of attending presidents, which prompted the resentment of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent an email to the media with a "final statement" from the summit, but this is just a statement by President Humala and not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of the South American and Arab countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA) and, even on this occasion, the originally promised Lima Declaration was not released, although it was fervently required by the press.
The official ASPA website shows that the document was released last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities sought to ensure broadcasting for all journalists, but to completely prevent the supply of information.
The summit ended, among other things, with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Hague Court of Hauga, which is in dispute over the border between the two countries.
President of Peru Ollanta Humala and President of Chile Sebastián Piñera met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will begin hearing the dispute launched by Lima against Santiago on Monday, with a hearing of the defence of the two parties.
"We will undergo and execute a judgment that will resolve the dispute we are hearing in this international court today," President Humala said, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"The Chile was, is and will be a country respecting international law, a peaceful resolution of disputes, a convention and an international court," Piñera said, greeting President Humal with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that he would submit to the International Court of Justice's ruling was made public after Colombia adopted the Bogota Pact this week, in submitting to the judgments of the International Court ruling on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, and Colombia considered the decision to be wholly flawed.
The summit was held without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 following the dismissal of then-President Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening the morning speeches and the end of the Lima summit shortly after noon.
The president read out the final document, informing that 16 agreements had been adopted and action had been planned for 31 projects between South American countries, with investment of $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the member countries of the UNASUR would take "important steps towards the target of South American citizenship, for which residence agreements are extended."
He reported that actions were supported to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil uncertainty and international organised crime, to improve the availability of medicines and the cheap internet in all corners of South America, and to joint and effective measures against the risks of natural disasters."
When Europe is in crisis, "the economic consolidation (Latin America) has no winning essence, but is intended to be used to expand our productivity and to show our nations a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve transport links between the various locations in South America, especially rural and border areas... to make our countries more closely connected and form new economic links," the Peruvian president said in the reading speech.
He mentioned that five of these projects involved Peru and the transiposites of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and the other two concerned a better link with Ecuador, but did not give more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return to the Union of South American Nations" from which it is currently excluded.
Another of the issues highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful area that is whole and has good neighbourly relations.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before attending the regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega in Mexico on Saturday to hear with respect the International Court of Justice's judgment on the maritime border dispute disputed by Bogotha.
"It is possible that I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will discuss all the solutions, none are excluded, nor the treaty with Nicaragua that would require negotiations with this country," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we should conduct the negotiations in the most civilised and considerate possible form possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico to attend the inauguration of the country's president, Enrique Peña Nita.
As part of the summit, EU Defence Ministers tentatively met to approve the Action Plan for 2013, which seeks to strengthen the dialogue and consensus on the field of defence.
UNASUR members are Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guiana, Suriname and Paraguay, although the latter is currently out of the question.
Peru is the interim chairman of this regional bloc.
